{"id":"2012.11584","submitter":"Ben Stefanek","authors":"Wolfram Ratzinger, Pedro Schwaller and Ben A. Stefanek","title":"Gravitational Waves from an Axion-Dark Photon System: A Lattice Study","comments":"27 pages, 9 figures. The source material includes the GW spectra in\n  tabulated form. Version submitted for publication","journal-ref":"SciPost Phys. 11, 001 (2021)","doi":"10.21468/SciPostPhys.11.1.001","report-no":"MITP-20-086, ZU-TH-57/20","categories":"astro-ph.CO hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work, we present a lattice study of an axion - dark photon system in\nthe early Universe and show that the stochastic gravitational wave (GW)\nbackground produced by this system may be probed by future GW experiments\nacross a vast range of frequencies. The numerical simulation on the lattice\nallows us to take into account non-linear backreaction effects and enables us\nto accurately predict the final relic abundance of the axion or axion-like\nparticle (ALP) as well as its inhomogeneities, and gives a more precise\nprediction of the GW spectrum. Importantly, we find that the GW spectrum has\nmore power at high momenta due to $2\\rightarrow1$ processes. Furthermore, we\nfind the degree of polarization of the peak of the GW spectrum depends on the\nALP-dark photon coupling and that the polarization can be washed out or even\nflipped for large values thereof. In line with recent results in the\nliterature, we find the ALP relic abundance may be suppressed by two orders of\nmagnitude and discuss possible extensions of the model that expand the viable\nparameter space. Finally, we discuss the possibility to probe ultralight ALP\ndark matter via spectral distortions of the CMB.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Dec 2020 18:59:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 5 Jan 2021 11:09:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-07"}
